04674nam a22005295i 9780822398868DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20002000ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223988687 a10.1515/97808223988682doi  a(DE-B1597)552670  a(OCoLC)1170361677  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aHIS0010002bisacsh04a916  aHL 38432rvk1 aPark, Mungo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTravels in the Interior Districts of Africa /cMungo Park; ed. by Kate Ferguson Marsters. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2000] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (416 p.) :b12 illustrations, 16 tables, 5 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures and Maps -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tNote on the Text -- tChronology of Mungo Park's Life -- tPark's Instructions -- tTRAVELS IN THE INTERIOR DISTRICTS OF AFRICA -- tTitle Page -- tDedication -- tPreface -- tContents -- tExplanation of African Words -- tSubscribers' Names -- tTravels in the Interior of Mrica -- tA Vocabulary of the Mandingo Language -- tQuestions and Answers That May Be Useful in the West Indies -- tAppendix: Geographical Illustrations of Mr. Park'sJourney, by Major Rennell -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMungo Park’s Travels in the Interior Districts of Africa has long been regarded as a classic of African travel literature. In fulfilling his mission to find the Niger River and in documenting its potential as an inland waterway for trade, Park was significant in opening Africa to European economic interests. His modest, low-key heroism made it possible for the British public to imagine themselves as a welcomed force in Africa. As a tale of adventure and survival, it has inspired the imaginations of readers since its first publication in 1799 and writers from Wordsworth and Melville to Conrad, Hemingway, and T. Coreghessan Boyle have acknowledged the influence of Park’s narrative on their work.Unlike the large expeditions that followed him, Park traveled only with native guides or alone. Without much of an idea of where he was going, he relied entirely on local people for food, shelter, and directions throughout his eventful eighteen month journey. While his warm reaction to the people he met made him famous as a sentimental traveler, his chronicle also provides a rare written record of the lives of ordinary people in West Africa before European intervention. His accounts of war, politics, and the spread of Islam, as well as his constant confrontations with slavery as practiced in eighteenth-century West Africa, are as valuable today as they were in 1799. In preparing this new edition, editor Kate Ferguson Marsters presents the complete text and includes reproductions of all the original maps and illustrations.Park’s narrative serves as a crucial text in relation to scholarship on the history of slavery, colonial enterprise, and nineteenth-century imperialism. The availability of this full edition will give a new generation of readers access to a travel narrative that has inspired other readers and writers over two centuries and will enliven scholarly discussion in many fields.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aHISTORY / Africa / General.2bisacsh1 aMarsters, Kate Ferguson, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822398868zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822398868423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822398868/original  a978-